<h3 class="mbs-4">Mixing font families</h3>
<p>
  We can mix different fonts for different scripts. Here's
  Tahoma used for Arabic and Verdana used for English.
</p>
<div class="demo-container">
  <p class="font-tahoma" dir="rtl">
    نص حكيم له سر قاطع وذو شأن عظيم مكتوب على ثوب أخضر ومغلف
    بجلد أزرق
  </p>
  <p class="font-verdana">
    The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.
  </p>
</div>

<p>
  Mixing fonts can cause iconsistencies; look at the
  variance in stroke weight and line height between Arabic
  in the Tahoma font and English in Impact.
</p>

<div class="demo-container">
  <p class="font-inconsistency-demo">
    <span class="font-tahoma text-lg"
      >نص حكيم له سر قاطع
    </span>
    <span class="font-impact">
      The quick brown fox jumps
    </span>
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Pronunciation marks</h2>
<p>
  Some languages add pronounciation text or marks to their
  scripts, like Ruby or diacritics.
</p>

<h3>Ruby</h3>
<p>
  Ruby annotations are small texts placed above or to the
  right of the base text to give pronunciation guides,
  explanations, or to show the use of characters in East
  Asian languages.
</p>

<div
  id="ruby-demo"
  class="ruby-demo demo-container demo-container--cols"
>
  <p lang="jp" class="text-lg ruby-over">
    <ruby>
      東京 <rp>(</rp> <rt>とうきょう</rt><rp>)</rp>
    </ruby>
  </p>

  <p lang="jp" class="text-lg ruby-under">
    <ruby>
      東京 <rp>(</rp> <rt>とうきょう</rt><rp>)</rp>
    </ruby>
  </p>
</div>

<p>
  We can use the <code>ruby-position</code> property to
  control whether the Ruby appears above (default) or below
  the text. This is subject to the
  <code>writing-mode</code> and <code>dir</code> of the
  text. Try it out:
</p>

<%- include('../partials/writing_mode_buttons', { target:
'#ruby-demo p' }) %> <%-
include('../partials/direction_buttons') %>

<h3>Text emphasis</h3>
<p>
  We can use the <code>text-emphasis</code> property to add
  marks to text. This is often used in East Asian languages
  instead of italics or bold.
</p>

<div
  id="text-emphasis-demo"
  class="demo-container demo-container--cols"
>
  <p lang="jp">
    明日は<em class="text-emphasis-dot">晴れ</em>です。
  </p>
  <p lang="jp">
    明日は<em
      class="text-emphasis-sesame text-emphasis-under-left"
      >晴れ</em
    >です。
  </p>
</div>

<p>
  We use the <code>text-emphasis</code> and
  <code>text-emphasis-position</code> properties to style
  text emphasis. This is subject to
  <code>writing-mode</code>. Play with it and see:
</p>

<%- include('../partials/writing_mode_buttons', { target:
'#text-emphasis-demo p' }) %> <%-
include('../partials/direction_buttons') %>

<h2>Quotation marks</h2>
<p>
  Different languages use different quotation marks. We can
  use the <code>quotes</code> property to set the quotes for
  a language.
</p>

<div class="demo-container">
  <p lang="ar" dir="rtl" class="text-lg">
    <q>عن صابر ابن جابز قال <q>للصبر حدود</q></q>
  </p>
</div>

<p>
  We've explicitly set outer quotes to
  <code>"«" "»"</code> and inner quotes to
  <code>"‹" "›"</code> for Arabic in the above example.
</p>
